title: For Sale:  Remington Model 51 .32  VERY RARE
postcontent:
Remington Model 51 in 32 cal. Serial #PA7××××. Overall condition is very good, slight uniform thinning of original finish. Grip safety has 50% of the bluing remaining, very slight edge wear, but overall no rust or pitting, grips are in great shape. Action is tight and crisp. Bore has nice sharp rifling with slight pitting at breech end.  Date of manufacture 1918-1926.

The same gun model is selling for over $1,000 on armslist. They are a rare and hard to find gun.  I used this as a nice conceal carry gun. 

Specifications

Weight - 21 oz (600 g)
Length - 65⁄8 in (168 mm)
Barrel length - 31⁄4 in (83 mm)
Width - 0.9 in (22.9 mm)
Action - Hesitation locked
Feed system - Detachable single-stack box magazine
Sights - Post and rear notch

Here is a bit of history on this gem:

The Remington Model 51 is a small pocket pistol designed by John Pedersen and manufactured by Remington Arms in the early 20th century for the American civilian market. Remington manufactured approximately 65,000 Model 51 pistols in .32 ACP and .380 ACP calibers from 1918 to 1927, though small numbers were assembled into the mid-1930s.

John Pedersen designed or helped design many firearms for the Remington Arms Company. He had worked in concert with John Browning to design the Remington Model 17 which served as the basis for the Remington Model 31, Ithaca 37,Browning BPS, and Mossberg 500. He designed the Pedersen device that converted the M1903 Springfield into an autoloading intermediate-caliber weapon. Pedersen later worked for the US Army and provided competition to John Garandbuilding an autoloading rifle to fire a full-power rifle cartridge. His design used lubricated cases and a toggle-bolt system much like the Luger pistol but eventually lost out to the M1 Garand.Made in .380 ACP and later in .32 ACP caliber, it was marketed as a pocket pistol. While the European market embraced small-caliber pocket pistols, the American market favored revolvers. More expensive than the Browning-designed competition, the Model 51 was not much smaller. Furthermore, Remington was a company known for their long guns; their handguns had previously been limited to revolvers forced to play second fiddle to Colt in terms of sales.Due to these factors, the Remington Model 51 enjoyed only limited commercial success. If competing with cheaper single-action blowback autoloaders made sales difficult, the stock market crash made sales nearly impossible. 

General George S. Patton owned a Remington 51 and was thought to favor the weapon. 

Willing to entertain serious and reasonable cash offers, but no trades please. REDACTED

title: For Sale:  Very Rare Simson Rework 1916 Luger
postcontent: Very Rare Simson Rework of 1916 DWM Luger. Stock # MMH132816RT. SERIAL # 97xx. A very rare Luger variant that is referenced in “World of Lugers, Proof Marks” by Costanzo. The pistol was originally a WWI Luger, dated 1916, and was reworked somewhere between 1923-1935. Some of the known Simson markings on the pistol are the E/6 on the toggle, and the Crow/BC proof, which indicates acceptance of an out of spec item. The pistol was re-numbered during the rebuild, somewhat in the fashion of a Russian Capture, which, of course, this is not a Russian Capture gun. Grip conditionrates 85%, and the finish rates about 80%, with some freckling on both sides of the receiver, and some very noticeable pitting on the takedown latch. The pistol has a “Stark” magazine, the number does not match the gun. This is a very rare Luger that belongs in an advanced collection, and it should be regarded as an investment piece as well..

title: For Sale:  Remington Model 51 .32 VERY RARE
postcontent:
FOR SALE: REMINGTON MODEL 51 .32 VERY RARE

Serial #PA7××××. Overall condition is very good, slight uniform thinning of original finish. Grip safety has 50% of the bluing remaining, very slight edge wear, but overall no rust or pitting, grips are in great shape. Action is tight and crisp. Bore has nice sharp rifling with slight pitting at breech end. Date of manufacture 1918-1926.  This same gun is selling for over $1,000 on armslist. They are a rare and hard to find gun. I used this as a nice conceal carry gun. 

Specifications
Weight - 21 oz (600 g)
Length - 65⁄8 in (168 mm)
Barrel length - 31⁄4 in (83 mm)
Width - 0.9 in (22.9 mm)
Action - Hesitation locked
Feed system - Detachable single-stack box magazine
Sights - Post and rear notch

Here is a bit of history on this gem:

The Remington Model 51 is a small pocket pistol designed by John Pedersen and manufactured by Remington Arms in the early 20th century for the American civilian market. Remington manufactured approximately 65,000 Model 51 pistols in .32 ACP and .380 ACP calibers from 1918 to 1927, though small numbers were assembled into the mid-1930s.John Pedersen designed or helped design many firearms for the Remington Arms Company. He had worked in concert with John Browning to design the Remington Model 17 which served as the basis for the Remington Model 31, Ithaca 37,Browning BPS, and Mossberg 500. He designed the Pedersen device that converted the M1903 Springfield into an autoloading intermediate-caliber weapon. Pedersen later worked for the US Army and provided competition to John Garandbuilding an autoloading rifle to fire a full-power rifle cartridge. His design used lubricated cases and a toggle-bolt system much like the Luger pistol but eventually lost out to the M1 Garand.Made in .380 ACP and later in .32 ACP caliber, it was marketed as a pocket pistol. While the European market embraced small-caliber pocket pistols, the American market favored revolvers. More expensive than the Browning-designed competition, the Model 51 was not much smaller. Furthermore, Remington was a company known for their long guns; their handguns had previously been limited to revolvers forced to play second fiddle to Colt in terms of sales.Due to these factors, the Remington Model 51 enjoyed only limited commercial success. If competing with cheaper single-action blowback autoloaders made sales difficult, the stock market crash made sales nearly impossible. General George S. Patton owned a Remington 51 and was thought to favor the weapon. 

Willing to entertain serious and reasonable cash offers, but no trades please. REDACTED

title: For Sale:  LE ONLY - LWRC International M6 IC 14.7" 5.56 BLK (M6A2R5B14ICG-LE)
postcontent:
LWRCI’s new Individual Carbine was developed in response to the requirements of the U.S. ARMY’s Individual Carbine program. It features some radical new features while maintaining the same basic M4/AR15/M16 architecture.

The new IC and its variants feature our new fully ambidextrous lower receiver. Dual controls for bolt catch/release, magazine release, and fire control mean that right and left handed shooters can use the rifle to its full effectiveness. It also means that when the shooter transitions to their offhand side due to barriers or injury, they can effectively manipulate the controls without having to switch hands. This new lower receiver is compatible with all legacy AR15 pattern upper receivers.

The upper of the new IC is a further evolution of the M6A2-SPR platform introduced in 2011. It features a 2-position gas block, user configurable rail system, and a revolutionary new upper receiver that has the mounting base for the handguard machined as part of the upper receiver for added strength and reduced weight. The 2-position gas block has settings for Normal and Suppressed fire. The full size 14.7” IC is compatible with the U.S. M320 40mm Grenade Launcher, the M26 breeching shotgun and the M7, M9 or OK3S Bayonets. 

The new Individual Carbine from LWRC International is proof that at times, evolution takes a giant leap forward.
